  <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero__copy">
        <span class="hero__eyebrow">Real-world cases · Industry signal</span>
        <h1 class="hero__title">
          Where digital twins<br>
          <span class="accent">already ship.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="hero__lead">
          Eight cases, two contexts. The closest practical precursor in auto
          insurance — telematics-driven usage-based insurance (UBI) — alongside
          mature digital twin implementations in manufacturing, energy, smart
          buildings, and automotive engineering.
        </p>
        <div class="hero__meta">
          <span>4 UBI programs · CA + US</span>
          <span>4 adjacent-industry DTs</span>
          <span>All sources cited</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== LANDSCAPE — visual inventory ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="kpi-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Inventory · documented cases · 2026-05</span>
      <h2 id="kpi-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">What this page covers, at a glance.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2" style="max-width: 64ch;">
        The auto-insurance cases share plumbing with a digital twin — telematics,
        smartphone apps, behavioural signals — but feed a discount formula
        rather than a continuously-updated model. The adjacent cases run
        mature twins, but not on customers. Zero true customer twins in auto
        insurance at scale — the honest gap this project addresses.
      </p>

      <figure data-reveal data-delay="3" style="margin: 36px 0 8px;">
        <img src="assets/img/landscape.svg"
             alt="An inventory of three columns. Column one — Canada and US UBI — lists four telematics programs in white orange-dotted cards: Progressive Snapshot, Allstate Drivewise, Intact my Drive, Desjardins Ajusto. Column two — Adjacent mature digital twins — lists Siemens, GE, Microsoft, and Tesla as four dark cards. Column three — Customer digital twins in auto — shows a large dashed orange zero with the caption Zero true customer twins."
             class="illus illus--bleed">
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SECTION 1: AUTO INSURANCE TELEMATICS / UBI ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="auto-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Telematics &amp; UBI · Canada / US</span>
      <h2 id="auto-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">The closest precursor in the auto market</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        UBI is not a digital twin in the strict sense. A UBI program collects
        driving signals and applies them to a discount formula; a digital twin
        maintains a continuously-updated virtual model of the customer that
        simulates outcomes under different conditions. But UBI is the most
        data-rich, customer-personalized practice that exists in this market
        today, and it is what any future digital-twin offering will be
        compared against.
      </p>

      <div class="cards">

        <a class="card" href="https://www.progressive.com/auto/discounts/snapshot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="1">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="9"/><path d="M12 7v5l3 2" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_01</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Auto insurance · UBI</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Progressive Snapshot</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">Telematics program tracking braking, acceleration, night driving, miles, and phone use via app or plug-in device. Discounts apply at signup and at renewal. About 80% of customers earn a discount; ~20% see an increased premium. Progressive reports &gt;$1.2B in cumulative Snapshot discounts and a $322/year average saving for renewing customers.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2010s</span><span>United States</span><span>Progressive · CIO</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://www.allstate.com/drivewise" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="2">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 12l4-4m0 0l4 4m-4-4v9"/><path d="M21 12l-4 4m0 0l-4-4m4 4V7"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_02</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Auto insurance · UBI</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Allstate Drivewise</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">App-based UBI with a one-way discount: rates can stay flat or go down, but never increase from the data. Realistic savings cluster 7–15% for typical drivers; Consumer Reports' median is ~$324/year. Allstate's April 2024 data: Drivewise customers were 25% less likely to be involved in a serious collision than non-participants.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2010s</span><span>United States</span><span>Allstate · Bankrate</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://www.intact.ca/en/personal-insurance/online-services/my-drive/faq-mydrive-v2" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="3">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 7v10a2 2 0 002 2h14a2 2 0 002-2V7"/><path d="M3 7l9-4 9 4"/><path d="M9 11l2 2 4-4"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_03</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Auto insurance · UBI</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Intact Insurance — my Drive</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">Canada's largest P&amp;C insurer launched smartphone-based UBI in Ontario in 2013. Three behavioral inputs: <code>speed</code>, <code>focus</code>, <code>smoothness</code>. Built on Cambridge Mobile Telematics. 10% enrolment discount; up to 25–30% off at renewal for safe driving. Bidirectional adjustment after the 6-month observation period. Directly applicable to this project's Ontario geography.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2013–</span><span>ON · NS · NB · QC</span><span>Intact · ThinkInsure</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://www.desjardins.com/ca/personal/insurance/car-insurance/ajusto/index.jsp" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="4">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"><rect x="6" y="2" width="12" height="20" rx="2"/><line x1="11" y1="18" x2="13" y2="18"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_04</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Auto insurance · UBI</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Desjardins — Ajusto</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">Launched 2013 in Ontario and Quebec. Among the earliest 100% mobile-only UBI programs in Canada — no plug-in device required. 10% sign-up discount for the first 180 days; safe driving can lower premiums by up to 25%, riskier driving can raise them up to 20%. The bidirectional structure is what generated the most public privacy debate (CBC News, 2015).</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2013–</span><span>QC · ON</span><span>Desjardins · CBC News</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SECTION 2: ADJACENT INDUSTRIES (mature DT) ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="adjacent-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Mature digital twins · adjacent industries</span>
      <h2 id="adjacent-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Where the technology is no longer emerging</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Outside of insurance, digital twins have a decade of operational
        evidence. The four cases below were chosen because they have public
        performance data, not because they are the most-cited in vendor
        marketing. Each illustrates a different facet of the technology that
        will eventually transfer to customer-side modelling in financial
        services.
      </p>

      <div class="cards">

        <a class="card" href="https://www.siemens.com/global/en/company/stories/industry/electronics-digitalenterprise-futuretechnologies.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="1">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 21V8l9-5 9 5v13"/><path d="M9 21V13h6v8"/><path d="M3 21h18"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_05</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Manufacturing</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Siemens — Electronics Works Amberg</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">A digital twin of an entire production line, in operation for over a decade. Engineers test what-if scenarios virtually without halting production. <code>99.9%</code> quality maintained, defect rate down &gt;60%, production volume up 13× since 1990 on the same 10,000 m² floor with almost no headcount change, energy use down 20%. The reference case in industrial DT literature.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2010s–</span><span>Germany</span><span>Siemens</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://www.ge.com/news/press-releases/ge-launches-next-evolution-wind-energy-making-renewables-more-efficient-economic" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="2">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="2.5"/><path d="M12 9.5V4M12 14.5V20M9.5 12H4M14.5 12H20"/><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="9"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_06</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Energy</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">GE — Digital Wind Farm</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">Per-turbine digital twins on GE's Predix platform. Each twin runs up to 20 operating configurations to find the optimal pad-level setup, then keeps learning from real-time sensor data. GE reports up to 20% boost in wind farm energy production, per-turbine MWh gains 5–7%, profitability up to 20% higher per unit. Estimated industry-wide value: $50B.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2015–</span><span>Global</span><span>GE · HBR</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/products/digital-twins" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="3">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="2"/><path d="M3 9h18M9 21V9"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_07</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Smart buildings · PaaS</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Microsoft — Azure Digital Twins</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">A platform-as-a-service for modelling physical environments and assets. Used by Microsoft for its own smart-building experiences (pathfinding, hot-desking) and by partners including Willow, Johnson Controls, Bosch, Bentley Systems, Ansys, Samsung. Most relevant signal: the platform generalizes the DT metaphor. The same primitives (<code>DTDL</code> ontology, twin graph, change feed) that model a building can model a customer relationship.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2020–</span><span>Global · PaaS</span><span>Azure · MS Inside Track</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

        <a class="card" href="https://www.cloudflight.io/en/blog/learnings-from-the-digital-twins-data-architecture-of-tesla/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-reveal data-delay="4">
          <div class="card__head">
            <span class="card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 17h14M7 17V8h10v9M9 8V6a3 3 0 016 0v2"/><circle cx="8" cy="20" r="1.5"/><circle cx="16" cy="20" r="1.5"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="card__id">CASE_08</span>
          </div>
          <span class="card__tag">Automotive</span>
          <h3 class="card__title">Tesla — vehicle &amp; battery twins</h3>
          <p class="card__desc">Tesla maintains a digital twin of every vehicle it has sold. Sensor data uploads continuously, feeding models of battery state, motor function, and Autopilot behavior. Software updates are pre-validated against the population of twins before being pushed. Published research suggests battery efficiency gains up to 30% and a 20% per-kWh cell cost reduction with mature twin implementations. The clearest current example of a per-unit operational twin at scale.</p>
          <p class="card__meta">
            <span>2015–</span><span>United States</span><span>Cloudflight · arXiv</span>
          </p>
          <span class="card__arrow">Open source ↗</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== HONEST CAVEAT — pull quote ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="caveat-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Read this honestly</span>
      <h2 id="caveat-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Why these inform — but don't replace — the auto-insurance use case.</h2>
      <p>
        Every auto insurance case above is a UBI program, not a digital twin
        in the literature's sense. UBI feeds a discount formula; a digital
        twin maintains a continuously-updated model of the individual and
        simulates outcomes under counterfactual conditions. The two share
        plumbing — telematics, behavioral data, smartphone apps — but they
        differ in what the model is for.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every adjacent-industry case is mature, but not customer-side. Siemens
        models a factory; GE models a turbine; Microsoft models a building;
        Tesla models a vehicle. None of them models a person whose insurance
        premium depends on the model's output, with the latter knowing it.
        Bringing the technology over the line into customer twins surfaces
        questions the industrial cases have not had to answer: meaningful
        consent, the right to inspect one's own twin, the right to challenge
        what the twin says.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="pullquote">
        UBI is the floor of what customers already accept. Adjacent-industry
        twins are the ceiling of what the technology can do. The auto-insurance
        customer twin lives in the gap between them — and the gap is where the
        marketing message has to be earned, not asserted.
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        Which is why the simulator in this project is a research prototype. It
        is built deliberately to make those questions visible — what changes
        when a twin replaces a segment, what the customer sees, what the
        marketing message can honestly say. <a href="./simulator.html">Try it</a>,
        then read the <a href="./methodology.html">methodology</a> for what it
        does and does not claim.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== CTA ===== -->
  <section class="section section--deep">
    <div class="container container-narrow" style="text-align: center;">
      <blockquote class="pullquote" data-reveal>
        Eight cases. Sixteen primary URLs. Zero fabricated citations. The full
        reading list backing every claim on this page sits one click away.
      </blockquote>
      <p style="margin-top: 28px;" data-reveal data-delay="1">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="./resources.html">Open the reading list →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="./methodology.html">Read methodology</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

